5px.title: Evidential decision theories
5px.clickbait: Theories which hold that the principle of rational choice is "Choose the act that would be the best news, if somebody told you that you'd chosen that act."
5px.text: An "evidential" decision theory (EDT) is one which [action_conditional conditions on possible choices] using standard conditional probabilities, aka [1ly Bayesian updating].  The corresponding candidate for a [principle_of_rational_choice principle of rational choice] would be, "Choose that act which would be the best news, if somebody told you that you'd decided that way."  Contrast [-5n9] and [-58b].  While relatively few decision theorists advocate for EDT as the principle of rational choice, some do.  EDT is historically noteworthy for being the original formulation of the [18v principle of expected utility]--the formula was first written down with the most obvious kind of [action_conditional action-conditional], namely a standard [1rj conditional probability].  However, nobody called this "evidential decision theory" until [-5n9] existed for contrast.  See [58d] for a guide to issues surrounding the choice between evidential and other decision theories (as seen from the stance of [58b LDT]).

5rf.title: Toxoplasmosis dilemma
5rf.clickbait: A parasitic infection, carried by cats, may make humans enjoy petting cats more.  A kitten, now in front of you, isn't infected.  But if you *want* to pet it, you may already be infected.  Do you?

5ry.title: Transparent Newcomb's Problem
5ry.clickbait: Omega has left behind a transparent Box A containing $1000, and a transparent Box B containing $1,000,000 or nothing.  Box B is full iff Omega thinks you one-box on seeing a full Box B.
